[14:23:30] {"event": "tool_result", "tool": "view", "is_error": false, "result": {"status": "success", "file": "/Users/virginia.zambudio/PlaywrightAutomation/tests/home-page.spec.ts", "content": "395: //   /enewsletter-settings?email=<encoded_email>\n396: // No confirmation message is shown on the homepage itself.\n397: // Verification: URL matches /enewsletter-settings after submit.\n398: // ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n399: test(\n400:     'TC-83232 — Newsletter signup in footer accepts valid email and redirects to confirmation @newsletter @footer',\n401:     async ({ page }) => {\n402:         // Override the global 60 s timeout: Builder.io networkidle can take 30 s,\n403:         // plus the retry loop (~15 s) and the final waitFor (45 s). 180 s is safe.\n404:         test.setTimeout(180_000);\n405: \n406:         const homePage = new HomePage(page);\n407:         const { newsletter } = homePageData;\n408: \n409:         await test.step('Navigate to homepage', async () => {\n410:             await homePage.navigate(homePageData.urls.home);\n411:         });\n412: \n413:         await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {\n414:             // The newsletter section is Builder.io-driven: it is rendered as a\n415:             // direct child of <body> and requires both the page to be fully hydrated\n416:             // and a scroll-to-bottom to trigger intersection observers that mount it.\n417:             // Strategy:\n418:             //   1. Scroll window to the very bottom to trigger the observer.\n419:             //   2. Wait for network to settle so Builder.io lazy content can load.\n420:             //      Use a 30 s timeout (UAT is slow; 10 s was too short on CI).\n421:             //   3. Attempt scrollIntoViewIfNeeded on the locator itself (Playwright\n422:             //      forces the browser to bring the element into the viewport, which\n423:             //      re-triggers any intersection observer if the element exists in DOM).\n424:             //   4. Poll isVisible() in a retry loop with repeated scroll triggers for\n425:             //      up to ~15 s before the final waitFor.\n426:             await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n427:             // Allow additional time for Builder.io content to be fetched and rendered.\n428:             await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle', { timeout: 30_000 }).catch(() => {});\n429:             await page.waitForTimeout(1_000);\n430: \n431:             // Repeat scroll to bottom in case the page grew after Builder.io rendered.\n432:             await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n433:             await page.waitForTimeout(500);\n434: \n435:             // scrollIntoViewIfNeeded triggers intersection observers on elements\n436:             // already in the DOM but outside the viewport.\n437:             await homePage.newsletterEmailInput\n438:                 .scrollIntoViewIfNeeded({ timeout: 5_000 })\n439:                 .catch(() => undefined);\n440: \n441:             // Poll for visibility in a retry loop as a belt-and-suspenders guard.\n442:             // Increased retries and interval to handle slow UAT / CI environments.\n443:             for (let scrollAttempt = 0; scrollAttempt < 15; scrollAttempt++) {\n444:                 const inputVisible = await homePage.newsletterEmailInput\n445:                     .isVisible()\n446:                     .catch(() => false);\n447:                 if (inputVisible) break;\n448:                 await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n449:                 await page.waitForTimeout(1_000);\n450:             }\n451: \n452:             await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 45_000 });\n453:         });\n454: \n455:         await test.step('Fill valid email in newsletter input', async () => {\n456:             await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.fill(newsletter.testEmail);\n457:         });\n458: \n459:         await test.step('Click SIGN UP button', async () => {\n460:             await homePage.newsletterSubmitButton.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });\n461:             // The newsletter section can have an overlapping layout element on some browsers\n462:             // (e.g. Edge). Use force:true to bypass the actionability overlay check and\n463:             // dispatch the click event directly to the button element.\n464:             await homePage.newsletterSubmitButton.click({ force: true });\n465:         });\n466: \n467:         await test.step('Verify page redirects to /enewsletter-settings', async () => {\n468:             // Submit triggers a client-side navigation to /enewsletter-settings?email=<email>.\n469:             // This confirms the form was accepted and the user is routed to the preferences page.\n470:             await page.waitForURL(newsletter.expectedRedirectUrlPattern, { timeout: 45_000 });\n471:             await expect(page).toHaveURL(newsletter.expectedRedirectUrlPattern);\n472:         });\n473:     }\n474: );"}}
[14:23:57] {"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nThe task has two parts:\n1. The Stepwise automation-planning skill execution (creating AUTOPLAN-SPEC and AUTOPLAN-AUDIT files)\n2. Fix the 6 failing tests (from \"Additional Instructions\" / human guidance)\n\nThe human guidance context says \"Fix this issues\" and lists 6 failures:\n1. TC-83232 Newsletter - `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` not visible (Chromium, Edge)\n2. TC-83240 Login - `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` not visible (Chromium, Edge)\n3. TC-83238 Store selector - `p.cursor-pointer.text-primary` hasText `/set your store/i` timeout (Firefox, WebKit)\n\nWait — but looking at the actual code files:\n- `home-page.spec.ts` line 452 already has 45s timeout and the retry loop\n- `LoginPage.ts` already navigates to `/auth/login` with 45s timeout\n- `ProductDetailPage.ts` already has the dual-state fallback\n\nSo the FRAMEWORK-SPEC says these were already fixed. But the test failures still occur. The error messages reference OLD code:\n- Error 1: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 })` at line 414 - but current code at line 452 has 45s\n- Error 2: `await this.emailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 })` at `pages/LoginPage.ts:28` - but current code has 45s\n- Error 3: `await this.setYourStoreLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 })` at `pages/ProductDetailPage.ts:262` - but current code has the fallback\n\nWait — the failures listed are in the ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTIONS (human guidance at the top), not in a guidance file. Let me re-read the context.\n\nThe instruction says \"Playlist global context: Fix this issues\" — these are context about what failed before. The framework spec says these were already fixed. So the FRAMEWORK-SPEC and current code files show the fixes are already applied.\n\nThe primary task here is: **Create the Automation Implementation Plan** (AUTOPLAN-SPEC + AUTOPLAN-AUDIT). The test failures listed in \"Additional Instructions\" appear to be historical context provided to the skill about what was already fixed.\n\nBut wait — the error stack traces reference OLD line numbers (line 414, LoginPage.ts:28, ProductDetailPage.ts:262). The current home-page.spec.ts at line 414 is still the old wait (I see 412-414 in the error), but looking at the current code I read, line 452 has the 45s wait. \n\nLooking at error 1: line 414 in the error context but current file shows line 452 has the new code. So maybe the git tracked version still has old code? The git status shows home-page.spec.ts, LoginPage.ts, ProductDetailPage.ts are all modified (M). So the working tree has fixes but maybe there are still some issues.\n\nThe primary mission is: Create AUTOPLAN-SPEC + AUTOPLAN-AUDIT for the automation-planning skill. The test fix context is provided as background (the \"validated test cases\" discovery spec shows what was found and fixed).\n\nLet me focus on the automation plan creation. The plan should map validated test cases to page objects and execution sequencing.\n\nFrom the context:\n- Test cases being fixed: TC-83232, TC-83240, TC-83238\n- Existing test specs: home-page.spec.ts (TC-83225,26,28,29,30,31,32), pdp.spec.ts (TC-83235,36,37,38,39,40), plp.spec.ts (FTC_02_01_x, FTC_02_02_x)\n- Page objects: BasePage, HomePage, LoginPage, ProductDetailPage, SearchResultsPage, StoreLocatorPage\n- The plan session ID should be: AUTOPLAN-PLAYWRIGHTAUTOMATION-20260715\n\nActually, let me re-read the task. The AUTOPLAN task is about creating a plan for the existing fixes/automation, not generating new code. The \"validated test cases\" input is the DISCOVERY-SPEC which maps the 3 failing tests and their selector/wait strategy fixes. The \"framework architecture\" input is the FRAMEWORK-SPEC.\n\nThe automation plan should:\n1. Map each failing TC to the specific files/page object changes needed\n2. Define execution sequencing\n3. Validate against framework checklist\n\nThe plan specifically focuses on the 6 failures listed (TC-83232 × 2 browsers, TC-83240 × 2 browsers, TC-83238 × 2 browsers) = 3 unique fixes needed.\n\nBut the code already has these fixes applied (per current file contents). So the plan should document:\n- What was changed\n- Map TCs to components\n- Validate compliance\n\nLet me now create the AUTOPLAN-SPEC and AUTOPLAN-AUDIT files.\n"}}
